{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:10:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:10:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12134"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.1,0.5,0.02,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107222"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4664"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89677"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2280"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6511"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107222"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of left-sided chest pain. The pain is pleuritic and worse on inspiration. He describes a tight diffuse pain across the left chest with a specific point of tenderness in the mid-clavicular region. The pain came on suddenly while he was having breakfast. He initially experienced some shortness of breath which has now resolved. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is particularly anxious about having a heart attack as his father recently died from one. He has been in the Emergency Department for one to two hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals slightly reduced breath sounds on the left side. An ECG shows normal sinus rhythm. A chest X-ray shows a 3 cm apical pneumothorax on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Needle decompression","Insertion of a chest tube","Observation in Emergency Department for four to six hours","Chest CT","Immediate discharge with advice to see GP if symptoms worsen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a primary spontaneous pneumothorax. Recent evidence has shifted management away from invasive interventions towards conservative management in stable patients, regardless of the size of the pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation in Emergency Department for four to six hours\u003C/strong\u003E is now considered appropriate first-line management for uncomplicated primary spontaneous pneumothorax in stable patients. This approach is supported by high-quality evidence showing similar outcomes to invasive management but with fewer complications. The observation period ensures clinical stability before discharge, with arrangements for outpatient follow-up including a repeat chest X-ray in two to four weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle decompression\u003C/strong\u003E was traditionally recommended for larger pneumothoraces. However, current evidence suggests that this invasive procedure is unnecessary in stable patients and carries risks of complications. It should be reserved for patients with tension pneumothorax or significant respiratory compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of a chest tube\u003C/strong\u003E is overly invasive for this presentation. It is now reserved for unstable patients, those with tension pneumothorax, or failed conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest CT\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary when the diagnosis is clearly evident on a chest X-ray. It would expose the patient to unnecessary radiation without changing management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate discharge with advice to see GP if symptoms worsen\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as the patient requires a period of observation to ensure stability. Discharging after only one to two hours in the Emergency Department without proper observation could miss deterioration and places the patient at risk. Structured follow-up rather than contingent GP review is essential for monitoring resolution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary spontaneous pneumothorax in stable patients can be managed conservatively with observation alone, regardless of size.","A period of observation in the Emergency Department for four to six hours is recommended to ensure clinical stability before discharge.","Follow-up chest X-ray within two to four weeks is essential to confirm resolution of pneumothorax."],"references":["Walker S, Hallifax R, Ricciardi S, Fitzgerald D, Keijzers M, Lauk O, Petersen J, Bertolaccini L, Bodtger U, Clive A, Elia S. Joint ERS/EACTS/ESTS clinical practice guidelines on adults with spontaneous pneumothorax. European Journal of Cardio-Thoracic Surgery. 2024 May 1;65(5)","Gorrochategui, M., Niknejad, M. Pneumothorax. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. (accessed on 24 Sep 2022) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-4578.","Brown SGA, Ball EL, Perrin K, et al. Conservative versus Interventional Treatment for Spontaneous Pneumothorax. N Engl J Med 2020;382:405-15.","Roberts ME, Rahman NM, Maskell NA, Bibby AC, Blyth KG, Corcoran JP, Edey A, Evison M, de Fonseka D, Hallifax R, Harden S. British Thoracic Society guideline for pleural disease. Thorax. 2023 Jul 1;78"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89677"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12134"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89677"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T14:44:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T14:51:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4664"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107222"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data"